# AddRange doesn't throw System.InvalidOperationException if a collection was modified.


# Environment

Microsoft Windows 10 Pro
10.0.17763 N/A Build 17763
Visual Studio Professional 2017 - 15.9.10
**.NET Core 2.2.102**
Console Application

# Problem description and repro steps
Considering the following scenario and classes described:
```c#
    public class MyClass
    {
        public MyClass() { }

        public Guid Id { get; set; }
        public string Description { get; set; }
    }
```

```c#
          ///Sample code that adds three items in a List
           var list = new List<MyClass>
            {
                new MyClass { Description = "Mydesc1" },
                new MyClass { Description = "Mydesc2" },
                new MyClass { Description = "Mydesc3" }
            };
           //Creates a new Enumerable with the 2x the number of items in the 'list' object
            var newList = list.Select(o => new MyClass
            {
                Id = Guid.NewGuid(),
                Description = Guid.NewGuid().ToString().Substring(0, 10)
            });

            //At this moment in the .NET Framework < 4.7.2 an exception of type System.InvalidOperationException is thrown      
           //Due to the fact that the Collection was modified above, however in .NET Core 2.2 the exception is never thrown, even checking the checkbox to break on System.InvalidOperationException
            list.AddRange(newList);
```

**Found result:**
The application get stucked in the AddRange operation consuming resources.

**Expected result:**
An exception of type System.InvalidOperationException being thrown as in .NET Framework 4.7.2

